'''Meja Mwangi''' (born 27 December 1948)<ref name=Gale>[http://www.answers.com/topic/meja-mwangi Carol Brennan, "Meja Mwangi", Gale Contemporary Black Biography.]</ref> is one of [[Kenya]]'s leading [[novelist]]s.<ref name=contp>{{cite web|url=http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth02D3O532712627281 |archive-date=2007-09-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927231044/http://www.contemporarywriters.com/authors/?p=auth02D3O532712627281 |series=Contemporary Writers |title=Meja Mwangi |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
Mwangi has worked in the film industry, including [[screenwriter|screenwriting]], [[assistant director|assistant directing]], [[casting (performing arts)|casting]] and [[location manager|location management]].

==Biography==
He was born David Dominic Mwangi<ref name=Gale /> in [[Nanyuki]], Kenya, and was educated at Nanyuki Secondary School, [[:de:Kenyatta College]] and studied at the [[University of Leeds]] for a while.<ref name=bbc>He did not complete a full university degree at University of Leeds.{{cite web|url=https://literature.britishcouncil.org/writer/meja-mwangi|title=Meja Mwangi biography<!--, Agent: Annemarie Friedli-->|access-date=2016-10-26}}</ref> He then worked on odd-jobs for French Broadcasting Corporation, a British Council in Nairobi for Visual Aids Officer,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OgqgREKxjNoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Meja+Mwangi%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjt5tjk9vDPAhUniFQKHUPmB-QQ6AEIKjAC#v=onepage&q=%22Meja%20Mwangi%22&f=false|title=An H.E.B. Student's Guide Notes on Meja Mwangi's Kill Me Quick|chapter=|last=Chakava|first=Henry|publisher=Heinemann Educational Books (East Africa) Ltd|location=Nairobi, Kenya|year=1976|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref> before he turned to full-time writing. He was [[Fellow in Writing]] at the [[University of Iowa]] (1975-6).<ref name=Gale />

Between 1975 and 1976, Meja Mwangi stayed in the United States of America as a Fellow in Writing at [[Iowa University]] writers’ workshop. Mwangi, the path to a popular writer was never obtained casually. After prolonged period in the Kenyan and African publishing scene over the years, he moved to the US after the recognition in several awards and winning reputation.<ref name=nation>{{cite web|url=http://www.nation.co.ke/lifestyle/weekend/Meja-Mwangi--the-reclusive-writer-with-a-mighty-pen/1220-2111002-jetitvz/index.html|title=Meja Mwangi, the reclusive writer with a mighty pen|last=Ciugu |first=Mwagiru|publisher=Nation Media Group|date=2013-12-13|access-date=2016-10-24}}</ref>{{refn|name=nations|Writing has been very hard work for him. It was certainly not a very easy occupation, though as moving from Kenya to the United States, the literal environment as well as material for Meja Mwangi will be abundant to be advantages for his career.}}

American publishers who was interested him as a juvenile literature novelist started to issue his works, and those publishers also put on print ''Mama Dudu, the Insect Woman (2007)'',<ref>{{cite book|title=Mama Dudu, the Insect Woman|publisher=HM Books|location=Columbus, OH|isbn=978-1-84728-468-6|year=2007}}</ref> as well as two screen plays, ''Power  (2009)'', and ''Blood Brothers (2009)'' a work expanded from ''Mama Dudu, the Insect Woman''. His best known early work is a trilogy of ''Kill Me Quick'' (1973), ''Going Down River Road'' (1976),<ref name=goingd/> and ''The Cockroach Dance'' (1979),<ref name=cockr/> illustrating the urban landscape in Kenya with struggle against poverty and epidemic of AIDS.<ref>Dictionary of African Biography, via Oxford African American Studies Center database, accessed March 13, 2015.</ref>

